<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much PEX tube do I need per square foot of radiant floor?", answer: "Tube length per sq ft = 12 / spacing (in inches). At 12\" on center, you need 1.0 ft per sq ft. At 9\" OC, 1.33 ft per sq ft. At 6\" OC, 2.0 ft per sq ft. Add 10% for bends, headers, and the return run to the manifold. A 200 sq ft room at 9\" OC needs about 293 ft of PEX total." },
  { question: "How much heat can a radiant floor deliver?", answer: "At 110-120 °F supply water, 1/2\" PEX at 9\" OC delivers about 25-35 BTU/hr per sq ft depending on the floor surface. Bare concrete or thin-set tile: 30-35 BTU/hr/ft². Engineered wood over slab: 20-25 BTU/hr/ft². Carpet with pad: 12-15 BTU/hr/ft² (not recommended — the pad insulates the floor from the heat). For a 200 sq ft tile bathroom at 125 BTU/hr/ft² heat loss, radiant delivers about 5,400 BTU/hr — a perfect match." },
  { question: "What is the maximum loop length for 1/2 inch PEX?", answer: "About 300 ft maximum per loop for 1/2\" PEX to keep head loss under ~3-4 ft of water. 3/8\" PEX is limited to about 200 ft. 5/8\" PEX can handle up to 400 ft. Longer loops require larger circulators and cause temperature drop from start to end of the loop, leaving cold spots at the return end. If your calculated tube exceeds the max loop length, split into multiple loops of equal length from a manifold." },
  { question: "What tube spacing should I use?", answer: "6\" on center for high-heat-loss rooms (sunrooms, bathrooms with lots of windows), perimeter zones near exterior walls, and as the primary heat source in cold climates. 9\" OC for typical rooms with moderate heat loss. 12\" OC for supplemental warming in well-insulated rooms or secondary heat sources. Tighter spacing delivers more heat per sq ft and evens out surface temperature." },
  { question: "Can I install radiant heat under carpet?", answer: "It's possible but not ideal. Carpet pad has R-value 1-2, which blocks 30-60% of the heat output. Radiant floor under carpet delivers 12-15 BTU/hr/ft² vs 30+ for bare tile. If you must use carpet, choose a low-pile loop with a thin foam pad (R-0.5 or less) and run hotter water. Hardwood, tile, and stone are much better pairings with radiant floor." }
]) %>

